# GAS — The TREE Strategy

*The architectural, commercial and product strategy for Global Accommodation Systems, expressed through the TREE metaphor.*

*Maintained by Steve Driver. Last updated May 2026.*

---

## Why "TREE"

Most SaaS describes itself as a *platform*, *stack*, or *engine*. Those metaphors are cold, mechanical, and they map poorly to the actual hospitality business they serve. A hotel — especially an independent, owner-operated one — is a living, place-based, seasonal enterprise. The tree metaphor captures that, and it also captures the real architecture of GAS.

| Part of the tree | What it is in GAS |
|---|---|
| **Roots** | Google, Apple, Bing, Meta — the directories, analytics, search, business profiles. Nutrients in (traffic, data) and nutrients out (NAP, photos, schema, signals). Hidden but everything depends on them. |
| **Soil** | The wider internet — the medium everything grows in. Channel managers, OTAs, social platforms, payment networks. |
| **Trunk** | The website itself — the canonical surface, the structural identity. The PMS-as-website. |
| **Branches** | The functional surfaces — room pages, booking widget, blog, attractions, contact, calendar. |
| **Leaves** | Content — descriptions, photos, posts, alt text, multilingual copy. Renewed seasonally. |
| **Flowers** | Marketing surfaces — campaigns, ads, social posts, email. Bright, attention-grabbing, seasonal. |
| **Fruit** | Bookings — the harvest. Revenue outcome. |
| **Sunlight** | Guest attention. SEO and ads channel it onto the tree. |
| **Pruning** | Site Audit Pro — cutting deadwood, broken links, weak meta, stale content, missing alt text. |
| **Pollination** | Cross-site references, partner networks, agency referrals — connections between trees. |
| **Seeds** | New sites being spun up — Airbnb-to-website, agency referrals, organic growth. |
| **A grove** | An agency's portfolio — Elevate Schweiz, a destination consortium, a multi-property owner. |
| **A forest** | The whole GAS network at scale. |
| **GAS itself** | The substrate. Earth, water, the mycelial layer connecting the roots. Not a *system* — the soil that *systems* grow in. |

The metaphor is structural, not decorative. Each part of it maps to a real architectural decision and an actual product surface. The metaphor is used in marketing copy and brand storytelling. It is **not** used in UI labels — keep functional names (Site Audit, Inbox, Bookings) so support docs work.

