## The competitive wedge

### What Mews and similar systems get wrong

Mews picks up at the front desk and drops off at checkout. Everything **before** the booking (discovery, content, conversion) — which is where independent hotels actually bleed revenue — and everything **after** the stay (reviews, retention, loyalty) — which is where they fail to compound — is "use the marketplace".

| Stage | Mews | GAS |
|---|---|---|
| **Discovery** (SEO, ads, content) | "Not our problem — use the marketplace" | Built in |
| **Decision** (photos, descriptions, reviews) | "Use a CMS / use Revinate" | The website IS the decision surface |
| **Booking** | Basic widget, treated as checkbox | Core surface, opinionated, mobile-first |
| **Pre-stay comms** | "Use a third party" | Inbox + email |
| **Check-in** | Heavy focus — their strength | Lite |
| **In-stay** | POS, in-room services, billing | Out of scope (deliberate) |
| **Review request** | "Use TrustYou" | Built in via Revyoos/Repuso partners |
| **Return / loyalty** | "Use a CRM" | Built in (Guest 360) |

Mews charges per room per month. Their economics reward more rooms under management. Their economics do not reward a guest actually booking. GAS economics (subscription + payment fees + booking-driven add-ons) reward conversion. That alignment shapes every product decision over years.

### The segment Mews ignores

Mews is built for 30-300 room properties with staff. The PMS is the heart.

GAS is built for 3-30 room properties, owner-operated, no IT person, owner has 30 minutes a week for marketing. The website + bookings is the heart, PMS-light is fine.

Mews onboarding is 6-12 weeks with a consultant. GAS onboarding is 5 minutes from an Airbnb URL. That contrast alone defines the wedge.

**Don't compete with Mews on their turf.** Compete on the segment they can't profitably serve. AI lets one person + a system do what previously took a team — that's the unfair advantage in this segment.

