## The "no gaps" principle

If you leave gaps, things fail.

For the GAS target segment (owner-operator, 3-30 rooms, no IT person), coverage has to be **complete**. Every gap is the same as Mews's 6-week onboarding gap: the moment the user hits a wall and has to open Mailchimp / SEMrush / a spreadsheet / "ask Steve for help" — the promise breaks and they drift back to the tool soup they were trying to escape.

The rule isn't "do everything Mews does". The rule is **no gaps in the owner-operator workflow**.

"No gaps" doesn't mean GAS builds every gap itself. It means every gap is *covered*. Three patterns:

| Pattern | When | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| **Build it** | GAS has the data nobody else does | PMS, website, bookings, CRM, calendar, audit |
| **Partner with margin** | Someone else owns the integration, GAS gets reseller cut | Domains (OpenSRS), email (Workspace), payments (Stripe Connect) |
| **Partner without margin** | Commodity integration depth matters more than economics | Channex (CM distribution), Revyoos/Repuso (review aggregation) |

The "no gaps" principle is also a revenue principle. Every workflow that pushes the user to a third-party tool is a margin leak. Every gap closed = one more recurring margin line.

