## Revenue stack — the Shopify model

Subscription is the wedge. The ecosystem is the business. Shopify makes ~3-4× more from non-subscription revenue (payments, apps, shipping, capital, hardware) than from subscription. GAS has the same shape available.

| Stream | Mechanism | Status |
|---|---|---|
| **Subscriptions** | Standard / Pro / Bespoke tiers + Plugin-Only | Built |
| **Payments (Stripe Connect)** | Currently Standard OAuth; switch to Express → `application_fee_amount` ~0.5-1% per booking | OAuth built, fee uplift planned |
| **Domains** | OpenSRS / Namecheap reseller — ~$3-7/yr per .com margin, plus renewals forever | Planned |
| **Email hosting** | Google Workspace / Microsoft 365 reseller — ~$5-6 wholesale, $10-15 retail | Planned |
| **OTA distribution** | Channex passthrough, potentially margin | Built (passthrough) |
| **AI features** | Pro tier upsell + per-use credits | Partial |
| **Site Audit Pro / Inbox / Ads Reporting** | Add-on subscriptions | Spec'd / planned |
| **White-label / agency tier** | Highest-margin per seat | Planned |
| **Marketplace later** | Third-party app revenue share | Long-term |

Every stream recurs. Every stream compounds with site count.

### The compounding case

At 1,000 sites:
- ~$6,000/yr domain margin
- ~$18,000/yr Workspace margin (30% conversion @ $5/mo margin)
- ~Variable payments margin at ~1% of booking volume
- ~Subscription baseline
- Add-on subscriptions per pro user

Plus stickiness: moving away from GAS now means migrating the domain AND the email AND the booking history AND the CMS — high switching cost.

