## Risks and dependencies

### 1. Bus factor

One person + Claude is the team. Works at 50 sites; doesn't at 500. Will be asked by any agency / tourism board / enterprise prospect. Not "hire today" but plan for documented code paths, an explicit succession story, and a first-hire profile (customer-facing technical + docs).

### 2. Acquisition channel

Word-of-mouth and referrals get you 0→50 customers. Not 0→500. Needs a deliberate channel — SEO content on gas.travel, YouTube of the 5-minute demo, Channex co-marketing, agency partnerships. Without one, the tree has soil but no sunlight.

### 3. Onboarding past the wow

5-minute import gets them a site. Then what? Most SaaS dies between week 2 and week 6. Need an activation funnel: site live → first OTA → first booking → first message in Inbox → first month of analytics → renewal. Each step needs a nudge.

### 4. Pricing matrix complexity

Tiers + add-ons + reseller margins + transactional fees can become baroque. Successful SaaS keeps it to 3-4 tiers + 1-2 add-ons max. Consolidate before adding more.

### 5. Channex / Airbnb concentration

Two providers underpin huge swathes of the stack. If Channex changes pricing, gets acquired, deprecates an adapter — problem. If Airbnb decides "no, certified partners can't export listings to competing direct-booking sites" — bigger problem. Contingency: route via direct CM integrations + iCal fallback for any property.

### 6. Data portability as a trust signal

"Your systems, not our system" promises that leaving is possible. Need to build export — CSV of bookings, properties, guests, content. Most SaaS hasn't; absence is increasingly a buying objection. Building it ahead of time is a small project that doubles as a trust signal and a positioning lever.

### 7. Support model at scale

Steve handles support today. AI Chat helps. KB helps. At what scale do you tier (community → email → priority phone)? At what scale do you SLA (99.9% uptime, X-hour response)? Both are revenue levers and procurement requirements.

### 8. The gas.travel site itself

It's the conversion funnel for everything. Needs hard look — product story crisp, 5-minute demo video visible, pricing page, signup flow, trust signals.

### 9. Mews can copy the 5-minute thing within a quarter

If GAS gets visibility. The moat isn't the feature; it's brand + speed of iteration + bundled depth + the architectural inversion underneath it. Lead with all four, not just the feature.

### 10. The AI moat is under-articulated

Currently: AI Chat, AI translation, AI blog generation — all table-stakes. The real moat: AI revenue management, AI review responses, AI guest pre-stay automation, AI competitor monitoring, AI marketing spend optimisation, AI anomaly detection, AI photo enhancement, AI auto-fill of empty Web Builder fields. 500-engineer companies can't move at this pace. Deserves a dedicated track in the roadmap.

